							<p class="c3"><span class="d1 d6">Understanding and Creating an AIM Template</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">The</span><span class="d1 d6">&nbsp;</span><span class="d1">AIM Template Manager allows a user, who is familiar with AIM information model, to create an AIM template XML document containing controlled questions and answers based on known vocabularies such as SNOMED CT, RadLex, LOINC, etc. as well as user-defined terminologies. The Template Manager is a web application. The following figures contain red numbers. Each number has a brief description describing feature and/or functionality. &nbsp;</span></p><p class="d3"><img height="81.52199999999999" src="../images/image0.png" width="624.355"></p><p class="d3 d7"><span class="d1">Figure 1. Login Page</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Figure 1:</span></p><ol class="d0"><li class="d2" value="1"><span class="d1">A user needs to have an account in order to create AIM templates. Click on &ldquo;Request an account&rdquo; URL or button and enter user information.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Log in&rdquo; </span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Enter a user name.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Enter a password.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Check to box if a user wants to store the password to AIM Template Manager application.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Click &ldquo;Login&rdquo; button when user name and password have been entered.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Click &ldquo;Request an account&rdquo; to get an account, same as #1.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">To reset password, a user must be successfully logged in to the system.</span></li></ol><p class="d3"><span class="d1 d6">AIM Template Groups</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">The AIM Template Groups Tab contains a collection of AIM template containers belonging to a user. AIM template containers cannot be shared directly with other users in the system. Each AIM template container contains one or more AIM templates. It provides a convenient way of organizing a collection of similar templates related to a study. An AIM template container is captured as an XML document that can be consumed by an application capable of understanding AIM and AIM templates. </span></p><p class="d3"><img height="393.06500000000005" src="../images/image1.png" width="623.5699999999999"></p><p class="d3 d7"><span class="d1">Figure 2. AIM Template Groups</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Figure 2:</span></p><ol class="d0"><li class="d2" value="9"><span class="d1">Template Groups Tab</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Template Tab</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Lexicon Tab</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">About and Help Tab</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Group Name&rdquo; displays all AIM template containers belonging to the logged-in user.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">When a group name, an AIM template container, is selected (darker gray highlighted), the information about the selected AIM template container and all included AIM templates will be shown in the middle window, &ldquo;Group Members&rdquo;.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Group Memberships&rdquo; displays all the AIM templates in the database and indicates the ones that belong to the selected AIM template container.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add a new AIM template container.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete a selected AIM template container.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Copy a selected AIM template container.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Download a selected AIM template container to local computer as an XML document.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Upload an AIM template container XML document from a local computer to the server.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Edit selected AIM template container information.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Removes a selected AIM template from the selected AIM template container after a user selects a template in &ldquo;included templates&rdquo;.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Adds all AIM templates with checked boxes to the selected AIM template container and removes any that don&rsquo;t have a checked box in the &ldquo;Group Memberships&rdquo;.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Depicts an AIM template container that contains two AIM templates.</span></li></ol><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Notes: </span></p><ol class="d9"><li class="d4" value="1"><span class="d1">When an AIM template container is deleted, any AIM templates contained in the container will not be deleted.</span></li></ol><p class="d3"><span class="d1 d6">AIM Template</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">An AIM template consists of a set of related questions for a study. See &ldquo;What is Being Captured in an AIM Template?&rdquo; in the About AIM Template Creator. </span></p><p class="d3"><img height="323.73699999999997" src="../images/image2.png" width="624.462"></p><p class="d3 d7"><span class="d1">Figure 3. Templates</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Figure 3:</span></p><ol class="d0"><li class="d2" value="25"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Template Name&rdquo; contains a collection for AIM templates.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Template Components&rdquo; contains a collection of questions and answers related to a question. A question can be for Anatomic Entity, Anatomic Entity Characteristic, Imaging Observation, Imaging Observation Characteristic, Inference and Calculation.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Search Lexicon Terms&rdquo; contains a collection of local lexicons that reside on server.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">A user can enter one or more search terms (after a lexicon is selected) in order to search for a term or terms to be included as part of answers.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Click on the icon after search term(s) have been entered in #28.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add a new AIM template.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete a selected AIM template. &nbsp;</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Copy a selected AIM template.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Edit a selected AIM template.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add a component such as Anatomic Entity, Imaging Observation, Inference or Calculation. See &ldquo;What is Being Captured in an AIM Template?&rdquo; in the About AIM Template Creator.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete a selected component such as Anatomic Entity, Imaging Observation, Inference or Calculation.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Copy a component such as Anatomic Entity, Imaging Observation, Inference or &nbsp;Calculation.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add selected term in &ldquo;Search Lexicon Terms&rdquo; to a selected table header/row in &ldquo;Template Components&rdquo;.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add &ldquo;Anatomic Entity Characteristics&rdquo; or &ldquo;Imaging Observation Characteristics&rdquo; in Anatomic Entity or Imaging Observation respectively.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete &ldquo;Anatomic Entity Characteristics&rdquo; or &ldquo;Imaging Observation Characteristics&rdquo; in Anatomic Entity or Imaging Observation respectively.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete selected &ldquo;Allowed Terms&rdquo;</span></li></ol><p class="d3"><span class="d1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1 d6">Lexicons</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Lexicons are a collection of standard vocabularies such as SNOMED CT, RadLex and user-defined terminology. They are available on an AIM Template manager for convenience reasons. Since various lexicons contain ten of thousand of terminologies, it is not convenient for a user to search for terminology and manually enter a terminology to an AIM template. Terminologies can be grouped for a particular purpose. AIM Template Manager contains sample lexicons such as LIDC, RECIST and VASARI. Each lexicon can be added, deleted and edited. A lexicon contains a set of terminologies. A terminology may have one or more terminologies as its children. Each child in turn may have one or more of its own children.</span></p><p class="d3"><img height="289.87" src="../images/image3.png" width="623.675"></p><p class="d3 d7"><span class="d1">Figure 4. Lexicons</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">Figure 4:</span></p><ol class="d0"><li class="d2" value="41"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Lexicon&rdquo; contains a collection of lexicons.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">&ldquo;Lexicon Terms&rdquo; contains a collection of terminologies.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">A table heading for a terminology.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">A table heading for the children of a terminology.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add a new lexicon.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete a selected lexicon.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Add a new terminology.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Delete a selected terminology.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Copy a selected terminology.</span></li><li class="d2"><span class="d1">Search for a terminology in a collection of local lexicons that reside on the server.</span></li></ol><p class="d3"><span class="d1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="d3"><span class="d1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="d8"><span class="d1">&nbsp;</span></p>
